t1875.text: A brown guy walks around the airport in an unhurried pace, almost as if he has a significant transit. He watches people intently, almost to the point of discomfort to the subjects in question. Occasionally, he pauses, pulls out his phone, types, smiles, and puts it away. A Creep?

t1876.text: A pair of men at a bar demonstrate the highest level of excitement a tennis fan could express whilst watching Millman VS Federer. Per score: they drum their fingers on the table, two shakes of a clenched fist, & a sip of the drink. They relishing each other’s company & the sport.

t1877.text: An elderly man wearing a hi-viz jacket pushes a fire-engine-red 240 litre rubbish bin around a corner like an F1 driver around a chicane. His stride suggests urgency. His pace and single arm grasp on the bin suggests there is nothing in the bin. Regardless, He looks busy.

t1878.text: A man wearing a mint worth of silver in chains sets off the knife-arc. He gets pulled aside and gets run through proceedure by a woman of significant heft. Her cadence carries a specific tone one gets approaching the end of a long shift: strained patience, unnecessarily stern.

t1879.text: A woman cries whilst holding an infant. It coos and mewls. It attempts to puts one of its feet on its mother’s saddened face. She watches a man look back once before vanishing through security. Her face sours beyond description: streaks turn into streams. She turns & walks away.

t1880.text: An elderly couple sit at one of the airport cafes. They share a single mug of what appears to be coffee. He tips a bit of the coffee onto the table whilst picking it up. She looks at the spill, then at him, then digs out disinfectant napkins from her purse. She cleans the spill.

t1881.text: A young white couple make out in-front of the departure gate: an animated monument to passion. Every variant of asian stare as they walk around them. Other white people wear a vexed look as they try to coax eye contact. They finally uncouple lips after an eternity & proceed in.

t1882.text: A brown kid walks ten paces behind his parents & little sister. He’s wearing a grey jumper with the hood engaged, jeans, and sneakers. He wears an expression that suggests he is 30 seconds away from a biblical fuss. He walks as if the floor was magnetised & he were made of metal.

t1883.text: An air-hostess walks past: Bright red outfit, sky blue scarf around her neck. She knows she is being watched. She wears a smile that reveals nothing about her. Her stride is akin to the prance of a prized equine. The timbre of her footfall, no less exclusive. Another day at work.

t1884.text: A man & woman cry next to each other, separated by the impersonal single-serve seating solutions indigenous to airports. He buries his face in his palms; she props hers in her hand. I watch & ponder the cause of their grief, but no signs reveal the nature of their circumstance.

t1885.text: A little girl sits on a luggage trolley. Her tiny legs dangle like laundry over the bow. A man with similar hair to her, pushes the trolley across the road crossing. Her shoes scrape on the ground, making a distinct sound. Her dark, curly hair bounces in the wind. She is happy.

t1886.text: 2 asian women stand together in-front of the departures sign. One appears older, the other younger. An asian man wearing a surgical mask in a navy suit gestures ‘closer’ with his right hand whilst kneeling ten steps in-front of the women. The women smile: The sound of a shutter

t1887.text: A middle age man looks at his boarding pass. His gaze darts around, the canyons on his brow painted of uncertainty. He takes five steps and stands under the flight information screens. His face, devout in expression aglow in the blinding light of information. His brow relaxes.

t1888.text: A teenage girl walks alone. Her eyes wide, searching. Her face,tense and unacquainted. Her steps, steady and measured. As quick as a lightning bolt, her entire persona changes: movement and appendages aflutter. She skips, squeals, and hugs two other girls. She’s beaming now.
